name: acetic acid, heptyl ester
Reason: The target compound, acetic acid heptyl ester, can be broken down into its functional groups for this analysis. Starting with acetic acid, which has a melting point around 16.6 degrees Celsius. The esterification with a heptyl (C7H15) group generally lowers the melting point because it makes the compound less polar and more hydrophobic, resulting in diminished intermolecular hydrogen bonding. However, ester functional groups (-COO-) have oxygen atoms that enable hydrogen bonding, causing a slight moderation of the melting point decrease. Applying these considerations: Acetic Acid: +16.6, Heptyl Group: -70 (reduces polarity and intermolecular forces significantly), Ester functional group: +3.2 (provides some capacity for hydrogen bonding, lessening the drop in melting point).
